LAGOS – The National Council for Arts and Culture (NCAC) has promised to improve unity peace and social harmony in the country through its partnership with the National Youths Service Corps (NYSC). Otunba Segun Runsewe, the Director-General NCAC made this promise in his office in Abuja on Wednesday when he received Brigadier-General, Shuaibu Ibrahim, the Director-General of NYSC in his office. While unveiling a joint agenda tagged: ‘Partnership That Works,’ Runsewe said that NCAC and NYSC had similar mandate. ABUJA DOCTOR REVEALS HOW MOST NIGERIA MEN ARE NOW OVERCOMING TERRIBLE BEDROOM PERFORMANCE DUE TO THIS BRILLIANT DISCOVERY. DON'T BE A VICTIM! He noted that while the NYSC was established in 1973 by Gen. Yakubu Gowon’s administration in pursuance of the policy of Reconciliation, Reconstruction and Rehabilitation (3Rs), the National Festival for Art and Culture (NAFEST) was established by the same regime to foster national peace, unity and integration through culture. Runsewe further said that while NYSC scheme brings together young Nigerians to serve in states other than their own, NAFEST brings together contingents from the 36 States and the Federal Capital Territory (FCT) to showcase their cultural peculiarities and exchange cultural ideas. NANTS Urges FG To Begin Sensitisation Of Nigerians On AfCFTA Implementation Military Helicopter Gunships Hit Boko Haram Convoy, Kill Scores In Borno Runsewe appealed to all organisations to always accept corps members posted to them and treat with respect as they are in the service to the nation. In his response, Ibrahim commended Runsewe for accepting to partner with NYSC, which the NCAC boss described as partnership that works. On the issue of spread of Covid-19 in the NYSC camps, Ibrahim explained that all prospective corps members were screened and tested before being allowed into the camp. He added that NCDC had its their offices in all the orientation camps in the country to take care of any emergency that may occur. He assured parents, guardians and intending corps members would be screened, tested and certified fit before being allowed into the orientation camps.